THE number of infected people in the Absa Premiership is slowly increasing as clubs testing ahead of the PSL's proposed return to training. Kaizer Chiefs are the latest club to have confirmed Covid-19 cases within their squad. ALSO READ: THREE MORE COVID-19 CASES IN THE PSL Chiefs conducted preliminary tests last Friday, in line with PSL protocols ahead of clubs' return to training in the coming weeks, and two players have since tested positive."Following a series of Covid-19 tests conducted last Friday, two Kaizer Chiefs players’ results have come back positive from the laboratory," read a statement from the club website "A total of 70 individuals, including players, members of the technical team and other club officials were tested for Covid-19 in preparation for the restart of the 2019/20 season." "At the time of doing these tests, players and officials were screened and monitored by healthcare workers and team doctors. None of the people tested showed any signs or symptoms of Covid-19""All the players and officials were given different timeslots and did not come into contact with each other""The affected duo will be in self-isolation for the stipulated period of 14 days. They will be retested after the isolation period as required. If their tests come back negative, they will then be able to rejoin the team""Kaizer Chiefs’ medical team and management are working around the clock to provide the necessary support to the affected individuals and ensure they follow the guidelines" The Chiefs duo increase the number of confirmed cases by the PSL clubs to seven. Orlando Pirates Ben Motshwari was the first player to test positive. On Monday Bloemfonein Celtic confirmed that one of their player tested positive. Stellenbosch Fc also confirmed that three of their staff members have tested positive.